I've been reading your Mathematical Quotes - with great interest.  There
is one which prompts me to write to you.  The quote follows:
=20
"In the pure mathematics we contemplate absolute truths, which existed
in the Divine Mind before the morning stars sang together, and which
will continue to exist when the last of their radiant host shall have
fallen from heaven."
=20
The attritution is "E. Everett, speech at Gettysberg, 1865."
=20
I wasn't able to find an 1865 speech at Gettysberg but did find an 1863
speech at Gettysburg (with -burg in place of -berg).  Assuming this
latter was the right speech, a search of the text at
http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Gettysburg_Oration did not find the quote.
=20
Any ideas for finding a copy of the speech that contains the quote?
=20
Thanks!
